## 9. Client Integration Strategy

### How a user integrates Sentinel into their project

There are 3 tiers of integration:

### Tier 1: Direct HTTP (Zero Dependencies)

Any project can POST raw logs to your ingest endpoint:

```javascript
// In any Node.js project — zero dependencies
fetch("https://your-sentinel-host/firewall/api/ingest", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
  body: JSON.stringify({
    logs: {
      source: "my-app",
      severity: "high",
      message: error.stack || error.message,
      traceId: requestId, // optional — for correlation
    }
  })
});
```

### Tier 2: NPM SDK Package (`@sentinel/sdk`)

Publish a lightweight SDK that wraps the HTTP call with error handling, batching, and auto-capture:

```typescript
// @sentinel/sdk — what you'd build and publish to npm
import { Sentinel } from "@sentinel/sdk";

const sentinel = new Sentinel({
  endpoint: "https://your-sentinel-host",
  apiKey: "project-api-key",  // project-level auth (new feature needed)
  source: "payment-service",
});

// Manual capture
sentinel.captureException(error, { severity: "high" });

// Auto-capture — wraps process.on('uncaughtException')
sentinel.enableAutoCapture();

// Express middleware
app.use(sentinel.expressErrorHandler());
```

**SDK internals would:**
- Batch logs (buffer 5 seconds before sending)
- Auto-retry with exponential backoff
- Attach source, timestamp, traceId automatically
- Provide Express/Fastify middleware for auto-capture

### Tier 3: Sentry-Compatible Webhook

Accept Sentry's webhook format so users can configure Sentinel as a Sentry webhook destination — zero code changes to existing Sentry setups.

